  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">MOMenTUM: Mobile Microbial WaTer qUality Monitoring using DNA technology</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;	Short general project overviewIn Mozambique, as well as in many other developing countries, the microbiological quality of drinking water in Mozambique is insufficient. Diarrhea caused by pathogens in drinking water is one of the leading causes of infant mortality in developing countries.Current methods for measuring and monitoring microbiological water quality are not simple, nor accurate or fast enough and, moreover, based on an indicator organism, almost always E. Coli). As a result too few reliable data are available on the microbiological safety of sources and drinking water.Accurate data on water quality would help the government and other agencies to implement preventive measures in a timely manner and to apply limited resources effectively. It also facilitates the monitoring of water quality. Data on microbiological water quality and safety also help to bring about behavioural changes in communities.The MOMenTUM project demonstrates a new technology (the Two3 device) to quickly, easily and cheaply generate the data needed to meet these challenges. In the long term, the technology can replace current breeding techniques and generate more and better data on microbiological water quality.&#x2022;	Initial activities and results of the projectWork and results pilot project: The project is being carried out in the Nhartande valley in the city of Tete in Mozambique. A project is currently being carried out here (the Nhartande Verde project) to improve poor groundwater quality (which is used as a source of drinking water) through the implementation of simple preventive measures. The MOMenTUM project will be involved in this to clarify the microbiological water quality and the effectiveness of the preventive measures for the removal of microbiological contamination. Concrete areas for improvement are identified and discussed with the Nhartande Verde project. The innovative Two3 device is used to generate the microbiological data in the field. This demonstrates the added value of the device through a pilot project involving potential launching customers.</narrative>
  </description>
